The simplest models of logistic and Poisson regressions using tabulated subset data

Logistic regession model

Model description

This simplest model describes only presence or absence of whitefish larvae \(y\), not its density. Here the observational model is described as Bernoulli distribution given as:

\[y_i |m_i \sim Bernoulli(g^{-1}(m_i(x_i))),\]

where we assume logit transformation of the mean function \(m(x)\)

\[g(m_i(x_i))= logit(m_i(x_i)) = log\left(\frac{m_i(x_i)}{1-m_i(x_i)}\right) \]

The mean function \(m(x)\) follows the logistic regression model:

\[m(x) = logit^{-1}(\alpha_0 + \alpha_1\delta_1(x_1)+ ... + \alpha_6x_6(x_1) + x_2\beta_1 + ... + x_6\beta_5). \]

In this model:

\(\delta_d(x_1)=1\) if \(x_1=d\) and zero otherwise, \(\alpha_d \sim N(0,10)\) and \(\beta_d \sim N(0,10), 0, ..., 5\)

The priors are defined as:

\[\alpha_d \sim N(0,10)\] and \[\beta_d \sim N(0,10), d=0, ..., 5\]

The posterior distribution:

\[p(\alpha_0, \alpha_1, ..., \alpha_6, \beta_1, ... ,\beta_5 | y,x) = p(\alpha_0)p(\alpha_l) ... p(\alpha_6)p(\beta_1)...p(\beta_5)\prod_{i=1}^{n}p(y_i | \alpha_0,\alpha_1, ..., \alpha_5,\beta_1, ... ,\beta_5, x_i)\]

Performing logistic regression using Stan.

The environmental covariates are:

BOTTOMCLS - Bottom type classifiction, a categorical variable with the following classes: 0 = not shallow 1 = open water 2 = other 3 = sand 4 = sand/mud 5 = sand/stone

DIS_SAND - distance to sandy shore, continuous variable

FE300ME - The average fetch (opennes/exposure) over all directions, continuous variable

ICELAST09 - The last ice cover date in winter 2009-10, continuous variable

RIVERS - Influence of rivers (~weighted average distance to river mouths), continuous variable

SAL910WIN - Winter salinity in 2009-2010, continuous variable

The output variable is WHISUM - the number of whitefishes caught in sampling occasion.

In this simplest case we model only presence or absence of whitefish, because of which we transform it to 0/1 binary variable.

The Stan hierarchical model of logistic regression is given in the chunk bellow. We have used y ~ bernoulli_logit((x.beta)) instead y ~ bernoulli(inv_logit(x.beta)) since the function bernoulli_logit is numerically stable.

data {
  int<lower=1> N; //number of observations
  int<lower=1> Dx; //number of predictors + first column = intercept alpha_0
  matrix[N,Dx] x; //covariate matrix
  int<lower=0> y[N];
}

parameters {
  vector [Dx] beta;
}

model {
  //priors for alpha and beta coefficients 
  //all alpha and beta coefficients are involved in beta column vector
  //beta =[alpha0, alpha1, ..., alpha6,beta1,...,beta5]
  //Set week priors for intercept and all other covariates
  for (i in 1:Dx)
    beta[i] ~ normal(0, 10);
    
  //the likelihood  
  //y ~ bernoulli(inv_logit(x*beta)); - does not work; not stable numercally
  y ~ bernoulli_logit((x*beta));
}

Test model accuracy

Here we make model predictions from Stan model in R. Here 3 ways to make predictions are described: 1. Predict outside Stan: use estimated posteriors in Stan to build the model and generate the output outside Stan, in R. 2. Predict with Stan: define only data (x_test + estimated parameters) and generated quantities (define output y_test). Model and parameter parts are empty.
3. Fit-and-predict: except data (x_train, x_test, y_train), model (y_train) and paraeter parts I n Stan we define also y_test in generated quantities.

Here we apply the first approach. We use log regression model in R to simulate ypredicted. Use MCMC parameter estimates for beta (from x,y data) and xpredicted to obtain ypredicted.

We first take random sample from all estimated \(\beta\), all train x data, and simulate the logistic regression model in R to obtain ypred:

lin_comb <- x%*%t(beta)
#prob of success
#prob==prob1
prob <- 1/(1 + exp(-lin_comb))
#prob1 <- exp(lin_comb)/(1 + exp(lin_comb))
#dim(x)[1] - number of observations we want to see
# # of trials per observation = 1 = Bernoulli
#prob - prob of success of each trial, dim(prob) = 217x3200
set.seed(56)
#dim(prob)=217x3200
y_pred <- rbinom(dim(x)[1], 1, prob)
# Accuracy
mean(y_pred == y)
## [1] 0.6267281

We repeat the same procedure for estimating the accuracy using train data, but now usng thinned \(\beta\) estimates:

#1.2 test model accuracy via r using thinned beta estimates
lin_comb_bt <- x%*%t(beta_thinned)
prob_bt <- 1/(1 + exp(-lin_comb_bt))
set.seed(123)
y_pred_bt<- rbinom(dim(x)[1], 1, prob_bt)
# Accuracy
mean(y_pred_bt == y)
## [1] 0.6820276
#CONCLUSION: THE ACCURACY WHEN USE THINNED ESTIMATES IS BETTER

Conclusion: The acuracy when use thinned parameter estimates \(\beta_{thinned}\) is better.

Evaluating the model: CV, WAIC and DIC measures of predictive accuracy

In all these 3 measures the goodness-of-fit is calculated as the average likelihood of the data given the parameters (i.e., \(p(y|\theta)\) over the entire posterior, and flexibility is calculated by some measure of variability of the likelihood over the posterior.

As a base for this work I have used the model solution of Exercise 2, Week 5, of Advanced Bayesian Inference course, and also Chapter 7 of course book.

K-fold cross-validation log predictive density and effective number of parameters

The Stan model used for this task is:


data {
  int<lower=1> N; //number of observations - train data 
  int<lower=1> Dx; //number of predictors + first column = intercept alpha_0
  matrix[N,Dx] x; //covariate matrix
  int<lower=0> y[N]; //observed y values
  
  int<lower=1> Np; //number of observations - test data
  matrix[Np,Dx] xp; //covariate matrix - predicted
  int<lower=0> yp[Np];//predicted  y values
}

parameters {
  vector [Dx] beta;
}

model {
  //priors for alpha and beta coefficients 
  //all alpha and beta coefficients are involved in beta column vector
  //beta =[alpha0, alpha1, ..., alpha6,beta1,...,beta5]
  //Set week priors for intercept and all other covariates
  for (i in 1:Dx)
    beta[i] ~ normal(0, 10);
    
  //the likelihood  
  //y ~ bernoulli(inv_logit(x*beta)); - does not work; not stable numercally
  //y ~ bernoulli_logit((x*beta));
  y ~ bernoulli_logit(multiply(x,beta));
}

//define log_lik to be usd in LOO CV 
generated quantities {
  vector[Np] Lik;
  for (n in 1:Np) {
    //The log Bernoulli probability mass of y given chance of success  inv_logit(x[n] * beta)
    // here we compute likelihood, and take log in r-code. Because we need to take column means?
    Lik[n] = exp(bernoulli_logit_lpmf(yp[n] | xp[n] * beta));
  }
}

The \(k\)-fold-CV estimate is: \[\mathrm{CV} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \log p(y_i|x_i,D_{\setminus k(i)}) \approx \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^S \frac{1}{S} \log p(y_i|x_i,\theta^{s}) \]

where \(\theta^s\sim p(\theta|D_{\setminus k(i)})\) and \(D_{\setminus k(i)}\) denotes the data from where the block including the data point \(i\) is excluded. \(S\) is the number of posterior simulations, and \(n\) is the number of observations

data_cv <- cbind(x,y)
# shuffle the data so that cross validation is done with random divisions
rows = sample(nrow(data_cv))
df = data_cv[rows,]
x<-df[,-13]
y <- df[,13]


K = 10;              # 10-folds for CV
n_groups <- ceiling(nrow(df)/K) #number of K-groups for predicting
logLikest = c(); # lppd_tilde - log point-wise posterior predictive density estimates


for (i in 1:n_groups) {
  if (K*i < nrow(df)) {
    ind1 = (10*(i-1)+1):(K*i)    # indexes of test data for first n_groups-1 groups
    #ind2 = which(y != y[ind1]);  # indexes of training data - this is not correct code
    #since compare y values, which could be equal or not (0/1)
  }
  else {
    ind1 = (10*(i-1)+1):nrow(df)    # indexes of test data for last group
    #ind2 = which(y != y[ind1]);  # indexes of training data - not correct code 
  }
  # dataset for the ith fold
  dataset = list(Dx = ncol(x), N = length(y[-ind1]), y = y[-ind1], x = x[-ind1, ], 
                 Np = length(ind1), yp = y[ind1], xp = x[ind1, ])
  
  #inits
  set.seed(124)
  #init1 <-list(beta=as.vector(rep(0,ncol(x))))
  init1 <- list(beta=as.vector(rnorm(ncol(x),0,10)))
  init2 <- list(beta=as.vector(rnorm(ncol(x),0,10)))
  ## initializing with init2 does not produce samples in Stan
  ## ?? How to choose initial values of the chains?
  init3 <- list(beta=as.vector(rnorm(ncol(x),0,10)))
  init4 <- list(beta=as.vector(rnorm(ncol(x),0,10)))
  inits = list(init1, init2, init3, init4)
  
  # posterior samples
  post = stan("Log_reg_whitefish_CV.stan", data = dataset, warmup = 300, 
              iter = 1100, init=inits, control = list(max_treedepth = 15), pars=c("Lik"))
  #print(post)  
  #take out the last column, lp_
  M = as.data.frame(post)
  M=M[,-ncol(M)]
  # log point-wise posterior predictive density estimates 
  #head(M$Lik)
  logLikest[ind1] = log(colMeans(M))
  #print(logLikest[ind1])
}

KfoldCV = mean(logLikest)
#cat(paste("\nKfoldCV: ", KfoldCV))
#cat(paste("\nk-fold-CV*2n: ", -2*length(y)*KfoldCV))

As it is ilustrated in [the course book], the effective number of parameters depends on the data even in a fixed model with fixed true parameters. An estimate of effective numbers of parameters using the cross-validation measures is (the book, eq. 7.15):

\[p_{k-cv} = lppd - lppd_{k-cv} \] \(lppd\) is the log pointwise predictive density, and \(lppd_{k-cv}\) is the cross-validated pointwise predictive accuracy.

#eff_N_par<-lppd-KfoldCV
eff_N_par<-length(y)*lppd-length(y)*KfoldCV
#cat(paste("\neffective number of parameters: ", eff_N_par))

Widely applicable information criteria WAIC

This criteria is computed according the following formulae:

\[\mathrm{WAIC}=-2 \sum_{i=1}^n \log p(y_i|D) + 2p_{\mathrm{WAIC}} \]

where \[\sum_{i=1}^n \log p(y_i|D) \approx \sum_{i=1}^n \log \left( \frac{1}{S} \sum_{s=1}^S p(y_i|\theta^s) \right) \] and \(\theta^s\sim p(\theta|D)\), and \[p_{\mathrm{WAIC}}= \sum_{i=1}^n \mathrm{Var}_{post}[\log p(y_u|\theta)]\]

dataset1 = list(Dx = ncol(x), N = length(y), y = y, x = x, 
                Np = length(y), yp = y, xp = x)
post1 = stan("Log_reg_whitefish_CV.stan", data = dataset1, warmup = 300, 
             iter = 1100, init=inits, control = list(max_treedepth = 15), pars=c("Lik","beta"))

M1 = as.data.frame(post1)
#MM=MM[,-ncol(MM)]
MM=M1[,1:217] #lik columns
logLikest = log(colMeans(MM))

#ElogLik1 = log(apply(MM, 2, mean)) - same as logLikest = log_x

ElogLik =  apply(log(MM), 2, mean)  #E(log_x)

ElogLik2 = apply((log(MM))^2, 2, mean) #(E(log_x))^2

p_WAIC = sum(ElogLik2 - ElogLik^2)

WAIC = -2*sum(logLikest) + 2*p_WAIC
#cat(paste("WAIC: ", WAIC))

The effective number of parameters computed using WAIC criteria is defined as: \[p_{WAIC} = 2\left(lppd - \sum_{i=1}^n \log p(y_i|D)\right)\]

#effective number of parameters
#cat(paste("\neffective number of parameters: ", p_WAIC))

Deviance information criteria DIC

It i defined as: \[DIC = -2 \log p(y| \hat{\theta}_{\mathrm{Bayes}}) + 2p_{\mathrm{DIC}}\] where \[p_{\mathrm{DIC}} = 2 (\log p(y|\hat{\theta}_{\mathrm{Bayes}}) - \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{post}}[\log p(y|\theta)])\]

#first compute logLikfix
beta_post=M1[,218:229]

lin_comb <- x%*%beta_means
prob <- 1/(1 + exp(-lin_comb))
set.seed(56)

logLikfix = sum(dbinom(y, 1, prob, log=TRUE))

p_DIC = 2* (logLikfix - mean(rowSums(log(MM))) )

DIC = - 2*logLikfix + 2*p_DIC

The differences in both prediction accuracy and effective number of parameters between k-fold CV and other two measures WAIC and DIC are because k-fold CV uses n-10 data points to compute the posterior predictive densities. WAIC is usually preffered then DIC because it averages over posterior distribution rather than conditioning on a point estimate.

The biggest disadvantage of K-fold cross-validation is the higher computational time.

The Negative Binomial model using Stan log-parametrization

The Poisson distribution is a common choice to model count data. It assumes that the variance is equal to the mean. When the variance is larger than the mean, the data are said to be overdispersed and the Negative Binomial distribution can be used.

In Stan the Negative Binomial distrinution is defined as:

\[NegBinomial (y | \mu, \phi) = \left( \begin{array}{c} y + \phi-1 \\ y \end{array} \right) \left( \begin{array}{c} \mu \\ \mu+\phi \end{array} \right)^{y} \left( \begin{array}{c} \phi \\ \mu+\phi \end{array} \right)^{\phi} \]

The mean and variance of \[y ~ NegBinomial(y | \mu, \phi)\] are

\[\mathbb{E}[n] = \mu\] and

\[Var[n] = \mu + \frac{\mu^{2}}{\phi}\]

In Stan model I have used log alternative parameterization \(\eta = log(\mu)\). For \(y \in \mathbb{N}\):

\[NegBinomialLog(y | \eta, \phi) = NegBinomial(y | exp(\eta), \phi) \]

The model in Stan:

data {
  int<lower=1> N; //number of observations
  int<lower=1> Dx; //number of predictors + first column = intercept alpha_0
  matrix[N,Dx] x; //covariate matrix
  int<lower=0> y[N];//response, whitefish counts
}

parameters {
  vector [Dx] beta;//regression parameters
  real<lower=0> phi; // the overdispersion parameter
}

transformed parameters {
  vector [N] eta; //linear predictor
  eta = multiply(x,beta); //use the log link
  //phi = 1. / reciprocal_phi;
}

model {
  //priors for beta and phi coefficients 

  //reciprocal_phi ~ cauchy(0.,5);
  phi ~ cauchy(0,3);
  
  for (i in 1:Dx)
    beta[i] ~ normal(0, 10);
    
  //the likelihood  - log alternatove reparametrization
  y ~   neg_binomial_2_log(eta, phi) ;
  
}

//define lik to be usd in k-fold CV 
generated quantities {
  vector[N] y_rep;
  vector[N] lik;
  vector[N] mu;
  
  mu = exp(eta);

  for (n in 1:N) {
    //log probability mass function 
    lik[n] = exp(neg_binomial_2_log_lpmf(y[n] | eta[n], phi));
    
    //random generator to check accuracy 
    y_rep[n] = neg_binomial_2_rng(mu[n], phi);
    // eta[n] = log(mean mu), mu=log(eta)
    if (eta[n] > 15) { 
            //15<29*log(2)=20.10127
            // To avoid erros like the below during the warmup. 
            // neg_binomial_2_rng: Random number that came from gamma distribution is 3.02668e+39, but must be less than 1.07374e+09  
          // https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/stan-users/4g2hbwtRELQ 
     y_rep[n] = -1;
     } else { 
       y_rep[n] = neg_binomial_2_rng(mu[n], phi); 
       //y_rep[n] = neg_binomial_2_log_rng(eta[n], phi); 
     }

  }
}

Evaluating the model: CV, WAIC and DIC measures of predictive accuracy

K-fold cross-validation log predictive density and effective number of parameters

The Stan model used for this task is:

data {
  int<lower=1> N; //number of observations
  int<lower=1> Dx; //number of predictors + first column = intercept alpha_0
  matrix[N,Dx] x; //covariate matrix
  int<lower=0> y[N];//response, whitefish counts
  
  int<lower=1> Np; //number of observations
  matrix[Np,Dx] xp; //covariate matrix
  int<lower=0> yp[Np];//response, whitefish counts
}

parameters {
  vector [Dx] beta;//regression parameters
  real<lower=0> phi; // the overdispersion parameter
}

transformed parameters {
  vector [Np] eta; //linear predictor
  eta = multiply(xp,beta); //use the log link
  //phi = 1. / reciprocal_phi;
}

model {
  //priors for beta and phi coefficients 

  //reciprocal_phi ~ cauchy(0.,5);
  phi ~ cauchy(0,3);
  
  for (i in 1:Dx)
    beta[i] ~ normal(0, 10);
    
  //the likelihood  - log alternatove reparametrization
  y ~   neg_binomial_2_log(multiply(x,beta), phi) ;
  
}

//define lik to be usd in k-fold CV 
generated quantities {
  vector[Np] Lik;
  vector[Np] mu;
  
  mu = exp(eta);

  for (n in 1:Np) {
    //log probability mass function 
    Lik[n] = exp(neg_binomial_2_log_lpmf(yp[n] | eta[n], phi));
  }
}

K-fold cross validation, K=10:

data_cv <- cbind(x,y1)
# shuffle the data so that cross validation is done with random divisions
rows = sample(nrow(data_cv))
df = data_cv[rows,]
x<-df[,-13]
y <- df[,13]


K = 10;              # 10-folds for CV
n_groups <- ceiling(nrow(df)/K) #number of K-groups for predicting
logLikest = c(); # lppd_tilde - log point-wise posterior predictive density estimates


#inits = list(init1, init2,init3, init4)
for (i in 1:n_groups) {
  if (K*i < nrow(df)) {
    ind1 = (10*(i-1)+1):(K*i)    # indexes of test data for first n_groups-1 groups
    #ind2 = which(y != y[ind1]);  # indexes of training data - this is not correct code
    #since compare y values, which could be equal or not (0/1)
  }
  else {
    ind1 = (10*(i-1)+1):nrow(df)    # indexes of test data for last group
    #ind2 = which(y != y[ind1]);  # indexes of training data - not correct code 
  }
  # dataset for the ith fold
  dataset = list(Dx = ncol(x), N = length(y[-ind1]), y = y[-ind1], x = x[-ind1, ], 
                 Np = length(ind1), yp = y[ind1], xp = x[ind1, ])
  
  # posterior samples
  post = stan("Negative_Binomal_whitefish_CV.stan", data = dataset, warmup = 300, 
              iter = 1100, chains=2, control = list(max_treedepth = 15), pars=c("Lik"))
  #print(post)  
  #take out the last column, lp_
  M = as.data.frame(post)
  M=M[,-ncol(M)]
  # log point-wise posterior predictive density estimates 
  #head(M$Lik)
  logLikest[ind1] = log(colMeans(M))
  #print(logLikest[ind1])
}

KfoldCV = mean(logLikest)

#cat(paste("KfoldCV: ", KfoldCV))
#cat(paste("k-fold-CV*2n: ", -2*length(y)*KfoldCV))

Deviance information criteria DIC

#first compute logLikfix
beta_post=M1[,218:229]
phi_post=M1[,230]
phi_means<-rowMeans(t(phi_post))
beta_means<-rowMeans(t(beta_post))
lin_comb_b <- x%*%beta_means
lambda_b <- exp(lin_comb_b)

set.seed(123)
logLikfix = sum(dnbinom(y, size=phi_means, mu=lambda_b, log=TRUE))

p_DIC = 2* (logLikfix - mean(rowSums(log(MM))) )##MM = lik columns 

DIC = - 2*logLikfix + 2*p_DIC
#cat(paste("DIC: ", DIC))
